Suggestions and comments from previous demo

  • Questions on the bibliometric evaluation model was raised.
    \(\rightarrow\) organization based
    Evaluation of KTH-output and higher precision. Will add further FAQ to the ABM to answer common concerns and questions.

  • Incorrect mappings and wrongly assigned publications
    \(\rightarrow\) based on school dialog and checks by researchers

  • Clearer view of incentives and how publications contribute to impact
    \(\rightarrow\) E.g. list of top-contributing papers and journals

Suggestions and comments from previous demo, contd

  • Data access and exports were requested.
    \(\rightarrow\) We are developing an API (currenlty JSON data) and an R package which bundles “public” data (without requiring database credentials).

  • Data sources were discussed, including possible additions \(\rightarrow\) We are testing Scopus data, to add this as complementary data (citation counts, Scopus coverage).
    We also indent to add functionality to the R package, to provide access to relevant open data sources (e.g.Microsoft Academic, Altmetric, Google Scholar etc).

Suggestions and comments from previous demo, contd

Some comments on KTHs goals and incentives with bibliometrics.
This should be an ongoing discussion within KTH leadership and the schools, with input from bibliometric group.

Finnish BU example

Who is Tuija Sonkkila, from Finland?

She is working at Aalto University Leadership Support Services. Altmetrics, SQL, Power BI, QlikView, data wrangling. She has written a paper on Metrics, Altmetrics, Data Visualization

She has developed Shiny apps covering bibliometrics analytics for Aalto University. Find more about her work at Tuijas web page and at her private blog at.

She also produces analytics and reporting on other things like staff mobility: https://github.com/tts/mobility2018
